        routeDescription: "The route takes the A10 towards Paris then the N141 to Cognac through the Charente vineyards.",
        introduction: "Cognac is a small town bearing the name of one of the world's most prestigious spirits. The great houses — Hennessy (founded 1765 by an Irish officer), Rémy Martin (1724), Martell (1715, the oldest), Courvoisier and Camus — have established their centuries-old cellars here where millions of litres of eau-de-vie age in Limousin oak barrels. The very air of Cognac is infused with the 'angel's share', that alcohol evaporation that feeds a black fungus (Baudoinia compniacensis) covering the town's walls and roofs — a phenomenon unique in the world. The Charente, a peaceful river flowing through Cognac, was once used to transport barrels to the port of Rochefort and the ocean. The town offers understated elegant architecture, pleasant public gardens and refined Charente gastronomy (grillons charentais, chabichou goat cheese, Charentes-Poitou AOP butter). A taxi is ideal for this journey, especially for those wanting to combine distillery visits and tastings: no driving concerns after glasses of VSOP and XO.",
        itineraire: "From Bordeaux, your driver takes the A10 towards Paris. The motorway crosses the Blayais and Bourgeais vineyards on the Gironde's right bank, then enters Charente-Maritime. After the Mirambeau exit, you head for Cognac via the N141. This national road crosses the Cognac vineyard, with endless rows of Ugni Blanc vines (the cognac grape, representing 98% of plantings). The chalky soils of Grande Champagne and Petite Champagne (cognac's two most prestigious crus) are revealed by white outcrops in the fields. Arrival in Cognac is via the Charente bridge with views of the great houses' cellars, recognisable by their characteristic blackness (the angel's share fungus). A10 tolls amount to approximately €10. The journey takes 1h20 in free-flowing traffic and can reach 1h45 if there is traffic on the A10.",
        conseils: "The great cognac houses offer visits and tastings year-round (reservation recommended): Hennessy (visit by boat on the Charente, €18-25), Rémy Martin (visit by small train through Grande Champagne vineyards), Martell (the oldest, immersive visit). Allow 1h30 per house. If visiting only one, Hennessy is the most spectacular thanks to the boat crossing. For knowledgeable enthusiasts, the Musée des Arts du Cognac traces the history of distillation. Cognac market (Tuesday and Friday mornings, Place François I) offers Charente specialities. In October, the Blues Passions festival transforms Cognac into a blues temple — return taxis to Bordeaux are highly sought after. Remember you can buy bottles directly from the houses: our boots easily hold 2-3 cases.",
