        introduction: "Capbreton is a unique seaside resort on the Landes coastline, the only one with a fishing port between Arcachon and Bayonne, across nearly 250 km of coast. This singularity is explained by the Gouf de Capbreton, an exceptional submarine canyon plunging over 3,000 metres deep just a few hundred metres from shore — the only submarine canyon in the world to approach so close to the coast. This oceanic trench, whose origin remains debated (tectonic fault or ancient bed of the Adour river which flowed here before being diverted to Bayonne in the 16th century), creates an exceptional marine ecosystem attracting tuna, dolphins and sometimes whales. The port of Capbreton, nestled in the Boudigau estuary, is a picturesque fishing port where trawlers land chipirons (squid), hake, sole and the famous line-caught tuna each morning. The Estacade, a long wooden pier stretching into the ocean (300 m), is Capbreton's symbol: a spectacular walk above the waves, it offers a panorama of the Landes coast and the Pyrenees. Built and rebuilt many times since the 16th century (the latest reconstruction dates from 2004), it protects the port entrance. Capbreton is also a renowned surf spot: the Plage de la Piste, to the north, offers regular waves for all levels, while the Santocha beach (south of the port) is more family-friendly. The town adjoins Hossegor, separated only by the Boudigau canal, forming a lively and complementary seaside conurbation.",
