        description: "Souillac, in the Lot department, is 2h35 from Bordeaux via the A89 and A20. Gateway to the Dordogne valley, Romanesque abbey and Périgord-Quercy crossroads.",
        routeDescription: "245 km — approximately 2h35 via the A89 then A20 towards Souillac",
        introduction: "Souillac is a small town of 3,800 inhabitants in the north of the Lot department, at the confluence of the Borrèze and the Dordogne, on the border between the Périgord Noir and Quercy. This strategic geographical position has made it, since the Middle Ages, a major commercial crossroads on the route linking Paris to southern France. The Abbey Church of Sainte-Marie de Souillac is a jewel of 12th-century Romanesque art. Its interior tympanum, moved inside the church during the Hundred Years' War for protection, features a unique iconographic programme in France: the dancing Prophet Isaiah (considered one of the finest Romanesque reliefs in the world), the Sacrifice of Abraham and an intertwining of fantastical animals of exceptional sculptural virtuosity. The church itself, with its three domes on pendentives (Périgord-Quercy style), recalls the Cathedral of Cahors, and the Souillac church is sometimes called the 'little cathedral'. The Museum of Automatons and Robotics, housed in the former Benedictine abbey, is unique in France: over 3,000 automatons from the 18th to 20th centuries, including the remarkable Roullet-Decamps collection (France's leading automaton manufacturers since 1832). The Lacave Caves, 8 km from Souillac, offer a magical underground spectacle: stalactites and stalagmites illuminated by ultraviolet lighting effects revealing natural fluorescence in the rock. Souillac is the ideal gateway to exploring the Dordogne valley: Rocamadour is 25 km, the Padirac chasm 30 km, Sarlat 30 km, Domme 25 km.",
        itineraire: "From Bordeaux, your driver takes the northern ring road then the A89 (Transeuropéenne motorway) towards Périgueux and Brive. You cross the Entre-deux-Mers vineyards, then the Libournais hillsides (Saint-Émilion below). After Périgueux, the A89 crosses the Périgord Noir, a landscape of wooded hills, deep valleys and golden stone villages. Around Brive-la-Gaillarde, the A89 joins the A20 towards Cahors. The Souillac exit (no. 55) leads directly to the town. Arrival through the Dordogne valley is magnificent: limestone cliffs, perched castles and the river compose a classified landscape. Combined A89 + A20 tolls amount to approximately €18. The journey is smooth, the A89 being less busy than the A10. In summer, the last few kilometres around Souillac can be congested (Dordogne tourism).",
        conseils: "The Abbey Church of Sainte-Marie is free and deserves careful attention (45 min): the interior tympanum with the dancing Isaiah is an absolute masterpiece of Romanesque art. The Automaton Museum (€8, 1h30) fascinates young and old. The Lacave Caves (€12, 1h, 8 km away) are spectacular, especially the final chamber in black light. From Souillac, excursions are endless: Rocamadour (25 km, 30 min), medieval city clinging to a cliff; Padirac chasm (30 km, 35 min), underground river by boat; Sarlat (30 km, 35 min), capital of the Périgord Noir; Domme (25 km, 30 min), bastide with panorama over the Dordogne; Marqueyssac (20 km, 25 min), hanging gardens. The Souillac market (Friday morning) is lively: Périgord walnuts, foie gras, cabécou (goat cheese), truffle in season (December-February). For canoeing, the Dordogne between Souillac and Beynac is a classic route (half-day, €20-25).",
        comparaisonTransport: "There is no direct TER Bordeaux–Souillac: via Brive (Intercités, 2h30) then TER Brive–Souillac (20 min), total 3h30-4h, €35-50. The TaxiNeo taxi at €300 — €370 is relevant for groups (3-4 passengers: €75-123 per person), families wishing to explore the Dordogne valley and those transporting equipment (bikes, canoes). By car, expect €25 fuel and €18 tolls. The taxi offers door-to-door and the option to stop at Sarlat, Rocamadour or Domme en route.",
