        routeDescription: "175 km — approximately 1h50 via the A65 towards Pau, Aire-sur-l'Adour exit",
        introduction: "Aire-sur-l'Adour is a small town of 6,500 inhabitants, sub-prefecture of the Landes, located in the heart of Gascony at the confluence of the Adour and the Brousseau. An episcopal city since the 5th century, it possesses remarkable religious heritage for its size. The Cathedral of Saint-Jean-Baptiste du Mas d'Aire (11th-12th centuries), built on the ruins of a Roman temple, is a massive Romanesque edifice whose crypt houses the sarcophagus of Saint Quitterie, patron saint of Gascony. According to tradition, Quitterie, a Visigothic princess converted to Christianity, was beheaded in the 5th century for refusing an arranged marriage; after her decapitation, she is said to have picked up her head and walked to the place where she wished to be buried (a classic hagiographic account of cephalophory). The 4th-century white marble sarcophagus is a masterpiece of early Christian sculpture, listed as a historic monument. The church is a stop on the Way of St James (Le Puy route, UNESCO World Heritage). Aire-sur-l'Adour is also a capital of the course landaise, a bloodless bull-running tradition where écarteurs face Landes cows in arenas. The Aire arenas, built in 1932, host formal courses from June to October. The town is at the heart of Landes foie gras country: the foie gras markets (November to March, Tuesday morning) are among the most renowned in the South-West. The Tursan vineyard (AOC since 2011), a few kilometres to the south, produces original white wines from the baroque grape variety, unique in the world.",
        itineraire: "From Bordeaux, your driver takes the ring road then the A65 (Autoroute de Gascogne) towards Pau. This recent motorway (opened in 2010) first crosses the Landes de Gascogne forest, then the rolling hills of the Bas-Armagnac and the Chalosse. The landscape changes gradually: pine forest gives way to maize fields, grazing meadows and Tursan vineyards. The Aire-sur-l'Adour exit (no. 6) leads directly to the town. The arrival is charming: the bridge over the Adour offers a view of the old town tiered on its hill, dominated by the cathedral silhouette. A65 tolls amount to approximately €15. The journey is very smooth: the A65 is one of the least-used motorways in France (dubbed a 'ghost motorway' by the press, as its high tolls deter many drivers who prefer the free national road). This is an advantage for our passengers: an almost deserted road, optimal driving comfort.",
        conseils: "The cathedral and its crypt with Saint Quitterie's sarcophagus deserve a visit (free, 30 min). Ask for the crypt keys at the tourist office if it is closed. The arenas are unmissable in season: courses landaises from June to October (€10-15), a unique spectacle of grace and skill (no killing, unlike the corrida). The foie gras market (Tuesday morning, November to March) is an authentic experience: fresh duck foie gras, confits, dried duck breasts, bought directly from producers (whole raw foie gras: €30-40 each). The Tursan vineyard can be visited: the cooperative cellar in Geaune (15 km) offers free tastings of this unique white wine made from the baroque grape. For heritage, don't miss the Church of Sainte-Quitterie du Mas (Romanesque, 11th century) and the walk along the Adour. Aire-sur-l'Adour is also a starting point for Armagnac country (Nogaro, Eauze, 30-40 km south-east).",
        comparaisonTransport: "There is no direct train from Bordeaux to Aire-sur-l'Adour: via Mont-de-Marsan or Dax (3-4h, €25-40, 1-2 connections). No Flixbus. The TaxiNeo taxi at €220 — €280 is relevant for groups (3-4 passengers: €55-93 per person), travellers continuing to the Gers or Béarn and those wishing to stop at the Tursan vineyard en route. By car, expect €18 fuel and €15 tolls. The taxi offers door-to-door, the tranquillity of the A65 (almost deserted) and the option to continue to Pau (65 km) or Mont-de-Marsan (30 km).",
